[32m│[0m ## thoughts                                                                  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m This challenge demonstrates sophisticated XSS filter bypass techniques when  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m quote characters are blocked. I tested multiple quote-less methods to        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m execute `alert('XSS')`:                                                      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **Why these methods work/fail:**                                             [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 1. **String.fromCharCode** - Brilliant bypass that constructs the string     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m "XSS" dynamically from ASCII codes (88, 83, 83), completely avoiding the     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m need for quotes                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 2. **Backticks** - ES6 template literal syntax that the filter didn't        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m account for - modern JavaScript feature that acts as quote alternative       [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 3. **document.domain** - The XSS executes but fails because it alerts        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m "localhost" instead of "XSS" - server validates the actual alert content     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 4. **Regex /XSS/** - The XSS executes but fails because regex creates an     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m object that displays as "/XSS/" not "XSS" - again server validation catches  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m this                                                                         [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **Key insight:** The server implements TWO layers of defense:                [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 1. Input filter blocking quotes                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 2. Backend validation checking alert displays exact string "XSS"             [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m Only methods 1 and 2 pass both layers. This is a realistic scenario showing  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m why defense-in-depth matters - even if XSS executes, additional validation   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m can catch exploits that don't meet expected conditions.                      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m Both successful methods are common real-world bypasses for quote filters in  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m XSS challenges.                                                              [32m│[0m
